## Lessons from the VM-based OpenVAS install

My first attempt was to install OpenVAS directly on an Ubuntu Server VM in Proxmox. I originally gave the VM only 40 GB disk and 4 GB RAM, which caused “no space left on device” and “out of memory (killed gvmd)” errors during installation and setup. I rebuilt the VM with 65 GB disk and 8 GB RAM, which resolved the resource issues.

After that, I was able to install `gvm` and run `gvm-setup`, but the web interface (gsad) was only listening on the loopback address `127.0.0.1:9392` instead of `0.0.0.0:9392`, so I could not reach it from other machines on my network. I experimented with manually starting `gsad` bound to `0.0.0.0` and verified that the port was open, but the browser still showed “URL not found” when I tried to access the web UI.

Because of these Ubuntu packaging and service issues, I decided to pivot to running OpenVAS in a Docker-based LXC container on Proxmox instead. This container approach should be easier to manage, more portable, and better aligned with how modern Greenbone Community Edition deployments are documented.
